<media alt="An illustration shows a reaction wherein alpha-fructose 6-phosphate undergoes reversible reaction to form beta-fructose 6-phosphate that forms beta-fructose 1 6-bisphosphate (FBP) by converting ATP (highlighted in green) to ADP (highlighted in blue). The structure of alpha fructose 6-phosphate shows a cyclopentane with an oxygen embedded at the top; the left corner is bonded to methylene group bonded to a phosphate ion; the center of ring shows an embedded oxygen; the top right position is bonded to CH2OH (pink hydroxyl group) at the top and a green hydroxyl group at the bottom; the lower positions on the ring are bonded to hydroxyl groups. The structure of beta-fructose 6-phosphate shows a cylclopentane with an oxygen embedded at the top; the left corner is bonded to methylene group bonded to a phosphate ion; the center of ring shows an embedded oxygen; the top right position is bonded to a green hydroxyl group and methylene group bonded to oxygen highlighted in pink bonded to PO3 to the power two minus (green); the lower left position on the ring is bonded to a hydroxyl group.">
