</media>
</figure>
</section>
<section id="sect-00004">
<title>Step <span class="magenta-text">4</span> of <link target-id="fig-00001"/>: Cleavage</title>
<para id="para-00004">Fructose 1,6-bisphosphate is cleaved in <emphasis effect="bold"><span class="magenta-text">step 4</span></emphasis> into two 3-carbon pieces, dihydroxyacetone phosphate (DHAP) and glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate (GAP). The bond between C3 and C4 of fructose 1,6-bisphosphate breaks, and a <m:math><m:mrow><m:mtext>C</m:mtext><m:mtext>═</m:mtext><m:mtext>O</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:math> group is formed at C4. Mechanistically, the cleavage is the reverse of an aldol reaction (<link document="m00276"/>) and is catalyzed by an aldolase. A forward aldol reaction joins two aldehydes or ketones to give a <emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis>-hydroxy carbonyl compound, while a retro-aldol reaction, as in this case, cleaves a <emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis>-hydroxy carbonyl compound into two aldehydes or ketones.</para>
<figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00005">
<media alt="An illustration shows a reversible reaction wherein fructose 1 6-bisphosphate reacts with a base and acid and forms glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate (GAP) and a compound in parentheses that further reversibly forms dihydroxyacetone phosphate (DHAP). The Fischer projection of fructose 1 6-bisphosphate shows a vertical 6-carbon chain. C1 shows CH2OPO3 to the power two minus. C2 is double bonded to a pink oxygen. C3 is bonded to a hydrogen on the right and hydroxyl group on the left. C4 is bonded to a hydroxyl group on the right (O is green) and hydrogen on the left. C5 is bonded to a hydroxyl group on the right and hydrogen on the left. C6 shows CH2OPO3 to the power two minus; a blue B having two electrons is shown on the right an arrow points from these electrons to H and another arrow from the hydroxyl group of C4 points to C4-O bond. An arrow points from the C3-C4 bond to C2-C3 bond. An arrow from the carbonyl bond of C2 points to H of H-A highlighted in pink; an arrow points from H-A bond to A. The Fischer projection of glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate shows a vertical 3-carbon chain. C1 is an aldehyde group (O is green). C2 is bonded to a hydroxyl group on the right and hydrogen on the left. C3 shows CH2OPO3 to the power two minus. The intermediate compound in parentheses shows a vertical 3-carbon chain. C1 shows CH2OPO3 to the power two minus. C2 is bonded to a pink hydroxyl group on the right. C3 is double bonded to C2 and single bonded to a hydrogen on the right and hydroxyl group on the left; a blue B having two electrons is shown on the right an arrow points from these electrons to hydroxyl hydrogen of C2; another arrow from the hydroxyl group of C2 points to C2-O bond. An arrow points from the C2-C3 bond to H of H-A highlighted in pink; an arrow points from H-A bond to A. The Fischer projection of DHAP shows a vertical 3-carbon chain. C1 shows CH2OPO3 to the power two minus. C2 is double bonded to a pink oxygen on the right. C3 is a hydroxy methyl group.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_29_05_005.jpg"/>
</media>
</figure>
<para id="para-00005">Two classes of aldolases are used by organisms for catalysis of the retro-aldol reaction. In fungi, algae, and some bacteria, the retro-aldol reaction is catalyzed by class II aldolases, which function by coordination of the fructose carbonyl group with Zn<sup>2+</sup> as Lewis acid. In plants and animals, the reaction is catalyzed by class I aldolases and does not take place on the free ketone. Instead, fructose 1,6-bisphosphate undergoes reaction with the side-chain  –NH<sub>2</sub> group of a lysine residue on the aldolase to yield a protonated enzyme-bound imine (<link document="m00219"/>), which is often called a <term id="term-00002">Schiff base</term> in biochemistry.</para>
<para id="para-00006">Because of its positive charge, the iminium ion is a better electron acceptor than a ketone carbonyl group. Retro-aldol reaction ensues, giving glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate and an enamine, which is protonated to give another iminium ion that is hydrolyzed to yield dihydroxyacetone phosphate (<link target-id="fig-00006"/>).</para>
