</section>
<section id="sect-00006">
<title>Steps <span class="magenta-text">6</span>–<span class="magenta-text">7</span> of <link target-id="fig-00001"/>: Oxidation, Phosphorylation, and Dephosphorylation</title>
<para id="para-00008">Glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate is oxidized and phosphorylated in <emphasis effect="bold"><span class="magenta-text">step 6</span></emphasis> to give 1,3-bisphosphoglycerate (<link target-id="fig-00008"/>). The reaction is catalyzed by glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate dehydrogenase and begins by nucleophilic addition of the  –SH group of a cysteine residue in the enzyme to the aldehyde carbonyl group to yield a <emphasis effect="italics">hemithioacetal</emphasis> (<link document="m00221"/>), the sulfur analog of a hemiacetal. Oxidation of the hemithioacetal  –OH group by NAD<sup>+</sup> then yields a thioester, which reacts with phosphate ion in a nucleophilic acyl substitution step to yield 1,3-bisphosphoglycerate, a mixed anhydride derived from a carboxylic acid and a phosphoric acid.</para>
<figure id="fig-00008">
<media alt="An illustration shows oxidation and phosphorylation of glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate. The reaction shows glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate forming three compounds in parentheses wherein a hemithioacetal loses blue NADH/H plus to form thioester to form the last compound in parentheses which expels blue HS bonded to an encircled Enz (the bond is intersected by a pink spiral line) to form 1 3-bisphospho-glycerate. The Fischer projection of glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate shows a carbonyl group (oxygen highlighted in pink) bonded to hydrogen on the right; the carbon of carbonyl is bonded to CH2OPO3 to the power two minus at the bottom; HCOH bond intersects the previous bond. A pink A-H is shown to the left of carbonyl group; an arrow points from carbonyl group double bond to H and another arrow points from A-H to A. Blue H bonded to S bonded to an encircled Enz (bond is intersected by a pink spiral line) is shown on the right; a blue “B” having two electrons is shown on the right of H-S; an arrow points from B to H another arrow points from H-S bond to carbon of carbonyl group. Hemithioacetal shows a blue sulfur bonded to an encircled Enz (bond is intersected by a pink spiral line) at the top the sulfur is bonded to a carbon at the bottom that is bonded to pink H-O on the left and H on the right; a blue “B” having two electrons is shown on the left; a NAD cation shows a benzene with embedded blue nitrogen cation on the upper right position the nitrogen cation has an open bond intersected by a pink spiral line; an arrow points from double bond adjoining nitrogen cation to the cation; another arrow points from the double bond on left to the adjacent bond clockwise; the third arrow points from C-H bond to the lower left position on the ring; fourth arrow points from pink O-H bond to O-C bond; fifth arrow points from B to H. Thioester shows a carbonyl group (oxygen highlighted in pink) bonded to blue sulfur bonded to an encircled Enz (bond is intersected by a pink spiral line)