<caption><emphasis effect="bold">Mechanism of step <emphasis effect="bold"><span class="magenta-text">6</span></emphasis> in <link target-id="fig-00001"/>, the oxidation and phosphorylation of glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate to give 1,3-bisphosphoglycerate.</emphasis> The process occurs through initial formation of a hemiacetal that is oxidized to a thioester and converted into an acyl phosphate.</caption>
</figure>
<para id="para-00009">Like all anhydrides (<link document="m00243"/>), the mixed carboxylic–phosphoric anhydride is a reactive substrate in nucleophilic acyl (or phosphoryl) substitution reactions. Reaction of 1,3-bisphosphoglycerate with ADP occurs in <emphasis effect="bold"><span class="magenta-text">step 7</span></emphasis> by substitution on phosphorus, resulting in transfer of a phosphate group to ADP and giving ATP plus 3-phosphoglycerate. The process is catalyzed by phosphoglycerate kinase and requires Mg<sup>2+</sup> as cofactor. Together, steps 6 and 7 accomplish the oxidation of an aldehyde to a carboxylic acid.</para>
<figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00009">
<media alt="An illustration shows a reaction wherein 1 3-bisphosphoglycerate forms an intermediate compound that expels ATP (highlighted in green) to form 3-phosphoglycerate. 1 3-bisphosphoglycerate shows a vertical 3-carbon chain. C1 is double bonded to a pink oxygen on the left and single bonded to a green phosphate group on the right; C2 is bonded to a hydrogen on the left and hydroxyl group on the right; C3 is CH2OPO3 to the power two minus; an ADP unit highlighted in blue comprising of two phosphate groups bonded to “adenosine” is shown on the right; the oxygen anions of the phosphate are connected with pink magnesium cation by dots; an arrow points from oxygen anion on left to green phosphorus of bisphosphoglycerate; another arrow points from green phosphorous oxygen double bond to the oxygen. The intermediate is similar to the reactant but the phosphate group is bonded to ADP highlighted in blue. An arrow from an oxygen anion points to the bond between phosphorus and the oxygen anion. An arrow from the P-O bond points to the oxygen. The structure of 3-phosphoglycerate is similar to the reactant but the phosphate group is replaced by a green oxygen anion.">
